//=========type Tree


🌳 1. General Tree

A tree where a node can have any number of children.

    A
  / | \
 B  C  D
No restriction on number of children
Used in file systems, org charts
🌳 2. Binary Tree

Each node can have at most 2 children:

Left child
Right child
    1
   / \
  2   3
🌳 3. Binary Search Tree (BST)

A special binary tree with ordering rule:

Left < Root < Right

Example:

      50
     /  \
   30    70
Used for searching, sorting
🌳 4. Balanced Binary Tree

Height difference between left and right subtree is small.

Examples:

AVL Tree
Red-Black Tree

Used to keep operations efficient: O(log n)

🌳 5. AVL Tree

A self-balancing BST

Condition:

Balance Factor = -1, 0, +1
Automatically rotates to stay balanced
🌳 6. Red-Black Tree

Another self-balancing BST with rules:

Every node is red or black
No two red nodes together
Ensures balance

Used in:

Maps, sets (C++ STL, Java TreeMap)
🌳 7. Heap

A complete binary tree used for priority queues.

Types:
Max Heap → parent ≥ children
Min Heap → parent ≤ children
      100
     /   \
   50     40

Used in:

Priority queue
Dijkstra algorithm
🌳 8. Trie (Prefix Tree)

Used for strings.

cat
car
cap

Structure:

c
 └ a
    ├ t
    ├ r
    └ p

Used in:

Autocomplete
Dictionary search
🌳 9. N-ary Tree

Each node can have N children

    A
  / | \
 B  C  D

Used in:

XML/HTML DOM
File systems
🌳 10. Segment Tree

Used for range queries.

Example:

Sum of range
Min/Max in range

Used in competitive programming.

🌳 11. Fenwick Tree (BIT)

Another structure for range queries (simpler than segment tree).

🧠 Interview Answer (short)

If interviewer asks:

"Types of trees?"

Say:

“There are several types of trees such as General Tree, Binary Tree, Binary Search Tree, Balanced BST like AVL and Red-Black Tree, Heap, Trie, and N-ary Tree. Additionally, for range query problems we use Segment Trees and Fenwick Trees.”